result.execSummary:
The defendant Cale F. Oelfke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer [Modifiers: Repeater], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.04(3).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superMiscConds.notes: The defendant shall comply with any treatment, evaluations and/or programming as deemed appropriate by a risk and needs assessment and the probation agent.  Defendant must sign any releases agent deems necessary to verify defendant's compliance with probation conditions.

Outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If reconfined or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. 

Court advised defendant of the DNA submission requirement.

charges.dispoDesc: Guilty Due to No Contest Plea

result.caption: State of Wisconsin vs. Cale F. Oelfke

records.addlTxt: Waive reading of the information.  Defense entered No Contest.  Court entered NGP on the defendant's behalf.

Court questioned defendant on his understanding of the waiver of preliminary hearing.  He stated he understood.  Court found that the defendant knowingly and intelligently waived his right to have a preliminary hearing.  Court found probable cause.

1:27 PM Defendant Cale F. Oelfke in court, in custody of the JCJ.  Attorney Emily Hynek in court for State of Wisconsin.  Attorney Bryant S Plank in court for Cale F. Oelfke.  Court reviewed the elements and potential penalties of the charge the defendant plead to.  He understood.  Defendant pleads No Contest to Count 1. Count 2 and related TR cases dismissed and read in for sentencing purposes.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant. Felony warnings given.  He understood. Defense stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, knowingly and intelligently entered his/her plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Found guilty of Count 1 Vehicle Operator Flee/Elude Officer contrary to 346.04(3) with repeater enhancer 939.62(1)(b) - Habitual Criminality. Count 2 DRI.  Defendant exercised his right to allocution. 
State is in compliance with victim rights.

Joint recommendation of a bifurcated sentence with 1 year initial confinement and 1 year extended supervision; would defer to the DOC on the ES conditions no special conditions. 66 days credit.  Atty Plank agrees on credit. 

Court adopts joint recommendation:  

Orders 2YR bifurcated sentence with 1YR IC and 1YR ES.  Not imposing any special conditions with ES.  Must undergo a risk and needs assessment and follow all conditions and recommendations. Costs can be paid during ES. Eligible for CIP and SAP. 66 days of credit.  
DNA submission requirement advised.

Plea/sentencing hearing on July 13, 2022 at 01:30 pm.
ALL PARTIES TO THE ACTION SHALL APPEAR IN PERSON FOR THIS HEARING.  THIS HEARING IS NOT BEING HELD VIA ZOOM.
